comments.text:
The space/rocket sector success you mentioned at the beginning is actually thanks to modi, but you gave the govt zero credit. 
The Modi government has opened up and expanded India’s space sector far beyond what was seen during the UPA era. Earlier, ISRO had a near-monopoly, and private companies were limited to being small-time suppliers. Between 2008 and 2014, India launched just 3 to 4 satellites a year , and private investment in space was almost nonexistent. In contrast, the Modi government has taken a big step by creating IN-SPACe in 2020—an agency dedicated to promoting and regulating private participation in space. As a result, by 2024, India had over 190 registered space startups , up from fewer than 5 in 2014.

To attract global capital, the government also allowed 100% FDI in certain areas of the space sector. This shift is already showing results: in 2023 alone, Indian space startups raised over ₹1,000 crore in private funding. ISRO’s launch activity has also picked up, with 7 to 8 launches a year after 2020, including high-profile missions like Chandrayaan-3 and Aditya-L1 . In short, while the UPA focused on building government capacity, the Modi government has focused on turning India into a space hub by enabling private innovation, foreign investment, and global collaboration.
